## What Problem This Solves

`extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts:1231` obtains a `ReadableStreamDefaultReader` via `response.body.getReader()` but never calls `reader.releaseLock()` or `reader.cancel()` in any code path. When the stream completes or errors, the reader lock holds the underlying stream open until garbage collection, potentially leaking resources.

This is **D3** dimension: resource leak via unreleased reader.

## Changes

- `extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts`: add `reader.releaseLock()` in the finally block (line 1465), alongside the existing `release()` call for the fetch guard

**Scope**: 3 lines added. The `release()` for the fetch guard was already present — only the reader lock was missing.

Label: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted | dimension: D3 resource leak

## Evidence

### Existing tests continue to pass

```
pnpm exec vitest run extensions/ollama/src/stream.test.ts

 Test Files  1 passed (1)
```

### Before/after

```
// Before
} finally {
  await release();  // releases fetch guard, but reader lock leaked
}

// After
} finally {
  try { reader.releaseLock(); } catch {}
  await release();  // both fetch guard and reader lock released
}
```
